As @adiga pointed out, interfaces determine the shape that values have. When using TypeScript with React, you may type your state and props with an interface.

An example using class components (see also [this][1] answer):

```
interface MyProps {}

interface MyState {
    foo: string;
    bar?: boolean;
}

class MyComponent extends React.Component &lt;MyProps, MyState&gt;  {
    constructor(props) {
        super(props);

        this.state = {
            // populate state fields according to props fields
        };
    }

    render() {
        ...
    }
}
```

An example using functional components:

```
  function MyForm(props: myProps) {
      ...
  }
```

As [this][2] Medium article points out, typing your state and props may help keep track of the shape of your state and props (and prevent errors). You may for instance decide to define all your interfaces in a single file (eg. `src/types/index.tsx`) and import your interfaces in your component files.


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36745013/interface-states-and-props-in-typescript-react
  [2]: https://medium.com/@rossbulat/how-to-use-typescript-with-react-and-redux-a118b1e02b76

