&gt; The class also has a constructor and each method relies on the constructor&#39;s parameters and on basis of that methods creates columns names of a table

The mighty `Regex` class uses the constructor pattern. 
 
```
Regex rgx = new Regex(pattern, RegexOptions.IgnoreCase);
var matches = rgx.Matches(input);
```

Oh, wait... there&#39;s this beauty:

```
var matches = Regex.Matches(input, pattern, RegexOptions.IgnoreCase)
```

----

You see, when it comes to class design there is no one solution that is best in all scenarios. 

It really depends. Really.

Friends were made, friends were lost over differences of opinions on this and this aspect of design is similar to the object-oriented programming vs functional programming discussion, in the sense that neither side of the argument won. 

In practice, the final solution will almost always use a bit of one and a bit of the other approach.  

 
Finally, the question is now closed as *primarily opinion based*. However:
 
  * there are better and worse solutions in a specific context;
  * it is important, the decision maek makes a practical difference;
  * you should be thinking about this (and even ask questions).

----

# Constructor+instance method vs a static method

When you want to preserve state over multiple calls it is natural to use a constructor to &#39;grab&#39; the values that will be used in multiple subsequent calls. 

----

# Your code sample

(Added after OP added their code to the question)

There are multiple issues with the code in the question. I will focus only on the constructor part. 

```
class Sql
    {
        public static Database db;
        public static Table tb;
        public static Server srv;
        public static String SheetName;
        public static List&lt;dynamic&gt; ColumnNames;
        public static List&lt;dynamic&gt; ColumnsDataTypes;
        public static DataTable DataTable;

        public Sql()
        {
        }

        public Sql(String sheetName, List&lt;dynamic&gt; columnNames, List&lt;dynamic&gt;DataTypes, DataTable dataTable)
        {
            SheetName = sheetName;
            ColumnNames = columnNames;
            ColumnsDataTypes = DataTypes;
            DataTable = dataTable;
        }
```

From the consumer&#39;s of this class point of view the biggest problem is that the constructor is lying to me. It&#39;s an instance constructor, but it sets static fields. 

```
var sql1 = new Sql(...);
var sql2 = new Sql(...);
// Ouch. &#39;sql1&#39; uses values that sql2 set.
```

This problem also applies to your methods setting the `db` fields. Since `db` is static `sql1.MethodX` will overwrite `sql2`&#39;s db.

## Suggestion

You should split the parameters into two classes:
  * shared among ALL database and server interactions throughout the lifetime of the application.
    These should be set in the static constructor or a static `Initialise` method
  * used only in the context of a single unit-of-work.
    These should be not static and they could be set in the contructor, or on the first call (e.g. `db`). 

Something like this could be a good start:

```
class Sql
    {
        private Database db;
        private Table tb;
        private Server srv;
        private String sheetName;
        private List&lt;(string Name, Type Type)&gt; columns;
        private DataTable dataTable;

        // This should not be needed
        // public Sql() { }

        //Maybe something like this?
        public static Init(Server srv); 
       

        public Sql(string sheetName, List&lt;(string Name, Type Type)&gt; columns, DataTable dataTable)
        {
            this.sheetName = sheetName;
            this.columns = columns;
            this.dataTable = dataTable;
        }
```

## `public Sql()`

The presence of a public parameter-less constructor suggests that you may be doing something like this:

```
var sql = new Sql(...); // Set the params;

(... some other place, another time)
var sql = new Sql().Method1();

(... some other place, another time)
var sql = new Sql().Method2();

etc.
```

Instead, you should be keeping a reference to `sql` and reuse it between calls or creating a new one but using the constructor **with** parameters.  

----

Note on dynamic and two lists.

The column tables can be a single list.
```
List&lt;dynamic&gt; ColumnNames;
List&lt;dynamic&gt; ColumnsDataTypes;
```

vs.

```
List&lt;(string Name, Type Type)&gt; Columns;
```

This way they will never get out of sync.

